# Monk Technologies - Agent code style

This rule defines the coding conventions for all bootcamp projects (`monk-research-assistant`, `monk-ticket-triage`, and any side labs). It is always in effect.

## Stack defaults

- Python **3.11+** only.
- Dependency manager: **uv**. The repo always has a `pyproject.toml` and a `uv.lock`.
- Type checker: **basedpyright** (or pyright). Type errors are real errors.
- Linter / formatter: **ruff**. Run `ruff check --fix` and `ruff format` before declaring a task done.
- LLM provider abstraction: **always** use `langchain.chat_models.init_chat_model` and `langchain.embeddings.init_embeddings`. Never hardcode a provider import.
- Web: **FastAPI** + **HTMX**. No React, no Next.js, no build step.

## Project layout

Every Monk Technologies agent project follows this layout:

```
.
├── app/
│   ├── __init__.py
│   ├── main.py                # FastAPI entrypoint (when applicable)
│   ├── graph.py               # LangGraph state + build_graph()
│   ├── llm.py                 # init_chat_model wrappers
│   ├── nodes/  OR  agents/    # one file per node/agent
│   ├── tools/                 # one file per tool
│   ├── memory/                # memory stores when applicable
│   ├── guardrails.py
│   └── ui/                    # HTMX templates
├── data/
├── evals/
├── deploy/
├── scripts/
├── Dockerfile
├── pyproject.toml
├── .env.example
└── README.md
```

## LangGraph conventions

- Define state as `class FooState(TypedDict)` from `typing`. No Pydantic for state.
- Each node is a top-level function `def x_node(state: FooState) -> dict` returning a **partial** state update (not the full state).
- Tools are top-level functions decorated with `@tool` from `langchain_core.tools`. They have docstrings written for an LLM reader (one sentence; describe what it does and when to use it).
- Compile the graph with a checkpointer in dev mode (SQLite) and in production mode (Postgres). Provide both paths.
- Use `astream_events(..., version="v2")` for any streaming endpoint.

## Function calling conventions

- Tool signatures use **strict type hints**, including return types.
- Tool docstrings end with the sentence "Use this when ...".
- For structured output, use `init_chat_model(...).with_structured_output(PydanticModel)` instead of parsing JSON manually.
- Always set a tool-call budget on tool-using loops (e.g. `max_iterations=8`).
- Validate outputs before trusting them: if a tool's output references a URL or an ID, verify the URL/ID actually came from a previous tool call.

## Error handling

- Never silently swallow exceptions. Re-raise with a contextual message, or log + return a fallback.
- Every external call (HTTP, DB, LLM) has a timeout.
- Retries: at most one retry. Use `tenacity` if the logic is non-trivial; otherwise a single try-except is fine.

## Observability

- Every project sets `LANGSMITH_PROJECT` in `.env`. All graphs are traced by default.
- When invoking a graph, always pass `config={"configurable": {"thread_id": ...}}` so checkpoints are scoped.
- Add `metadata={"user_id": ..., "feature": "..."}` to every top-level graph invoke so we can slice LangSmith data later.

## Cursor-specific patterns

- When generating a new file, **always include all imports**. The instructor and learners hate dangling `NameError`s.
- Prefer top-level functions over classes unless state needs to live on `self`.
- Keep files small. If a node file is over ~120 lines, split out the prompt builder into its own helper.
- Do not add boilerplate comments that restate the obvious. Reserve comments for *why* something is done a non-obvious way.
- After generating, run `ruff check --fix && ruff format` mentally and adjust.

## What never to do

- Do not write Terraform, Helm, or Kubernetes manifests. Cloud is via console + provided scripts.
- Do not hardcode model names other than as the default value of a `os.getenv` call.
- Do not hardcode secrets. Always read from env or from a secret manager.
- Do not commit `.env` (only `.env.example`).
- Do not invent libraries. If unsure, ask the instructor or read the existing imports.

## Reading material for the agent generating this code

When you (Cursor) write code under this style:

- Refer to the LangGraph 1.2.x API: <https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/>
- Refer to LangChain `init_chat_model`: <https://python.langchain.com/api_reference/langchain/chat_models/langchain.chat_models.base.init_chat_model.html>
- Refer to LangSmith evaluators: <https://docs.smith.langchain.com/evaluation>

If the user's prompt conflicts with this style, follow the user's prompt but flag the conflict in a one-line comment at the top of the file.
